    "heading": "When to Wear a Kimono",
    "content": "Kimono are reserved for more formal or culturally significant occasions where traditional attire is expected or appreciated. The most significant event where kimono are de rigueur is Coming of Age Day (seijin shiki 成人式) in January, when 20-year-olds celebrate their entry into adulthood with elaborate photos and ceremonies. Weddings (kekkon shiki 結婚式) often feature both the bride and groom in formal kimono, with the bride typically wearing a white kimono (uchikake 打掛) for the ceremony and a colorful one for the reception. Tea ceremony (chado 茶道) practitioners traditionally wear kimono as part of the aesthetic experience, with the choice of kimono indicating the season and level of formality. New Year (oshogatsu お正月) celebrations often prompt families to wear kimono when visiting shrines for hatsumode (初詣) - the first shrine visit of the new year. Graduation ceremonies also frequently feature kimono, especially for those participating in traditional ceremonies. Many tourists visiting Japan choose to rent kimono for photoshoots in historic districts like Kyoto’s Higashiyama or Tokyo’s Asakusa, where the setting enhances the traditional aesthetic. While formal kimono are expensive and require significant dressing time, semi-formal versions can be worn for less ceremonial occasions like restaurant visits in traditional areas or cultural performances."
