    "q": "Are there different styles of kimono for different seasons?",
    "a": "Kimono vary noticeably based on the season in both fabric and design. Summer kimono (nagagi 夏着物) are constructed from lightweight silk or cotton and often feature bright, cheerful patterns suitable for warm weather. Winter kimono (冬着物) are made from heavier fabrics such as wool or lined silk, and may incorporate warmer, darker colors. The sleeves (furi 振り) also differ; summer kimono have longer sleeves to promote airflow, while winter kimono have shorter or narrower sleeves. Seasonal motifs are important in kimono design: cherry blossoms and new green leaves for spring, wisteria and peonies for early summer, lotus and fireworks for late summer, maple leaves and chrysanthemums for autumn, and pine, bamboo, and plum (sho-chiku-bai 松竹梅) for winter. The placement of motifs adheres to seasonal etiquette; pine needles might appear on the hem for winter, but would not be seen on a summer kimono."
